INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3200','letter','1777-11-02','Fishkill','NY','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I understand, from Colonel Morgan, that all the Northern army were marching down on both sides the river, and would probably be to-morrow at New Windsor','ltr_alh3200.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3201','letter','1777-11-00','Albany','NY','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I arrived here yesterday, at noon, and waited upon General Gates immediately, on the business of my mission ; but was sorry to find his ideas did not correspond with yours for drawing off the number of troops you directed.','ltr_alh3201.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3202','letter','1777-11-10','New Windsor','NY','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I am pained, beyond expression, to inform your Excellency that, on my arrival here, I find every thing has been neglected and deranged by General Putnam','ltr_alh3202.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3203','letter','1777-11-12','New Windsor','NY','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','The enemy appear to have stripped New York very bare. The people there (that is, the Tories) are in a very great fright.','ltr_alh3203.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3204','letter','1777-11-15','Peekskill','NY','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','The troops now remaining with General Putnam will amount to about the number you intended, though they are not exactly the same. He has detached Colonel Charles Webb\'s regiment to you.','ltr_alh3204.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3205','letter','1778-06-26','Allentown','PA','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','We have halted the troops at this place. The enemy, by our last reports, were four miles from this (that is, their rear), and had passed the road which turns off towards South Amboy, which determines their route towards Shrewsbury.','ltr_alh3205.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3206','letter','1778-06-28','','NJ','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','The result of what I have seen and heard concerning the enemy is, that they have encamped with their van a little beyond Monmouth Court-House, and their rear at Manalapan\'s River, about seven miles from this place.','ltr_alh3206.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3207','letter','1778-07-20','Black Point','NJ','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','Inclosed I transmit your Excellency a letter from Count D Estaing. He has had the river sounded, and finds he cannot enter. He will sail for Rhode Island to-morrow evening','ltr_alh3207.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3208','letter','1778-07-23','Newark','NJ','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','The Count had received his expected despatches from Congress, and was to sail, as I mentioned before, the first fair wind.','ltr_alh3208.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3209','letter','1780-03-17','Amboy','NJ','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','The enemy are still in the dark about their fleet and army gone that way, as we gather from the Commissioners. They pretend to have little European news, though a vessel arrived two or three days since from England','ltr_alh3209.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3210','letter','1780-06-08','','','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','George','Washington','','individual','','I have seen the enemy. Those in view I calculate at about three thousand. There may be, and probably are, enough others out of sight.','ltr_alh3210.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
INSERT INTO media VALUES ('ltr_alh3211','letter','1777-11-09','New Windsor','NY','US','Alexander','Hamilton','','Israel','Putnam','','individual','','I cannot forbear confessing, that I am astonished and alarmed beyond measure, to find that all his Excellency\'s views have been hitherto frustrated, and that no single step of those I mentioned to you has been taken','ltr_alh3211.txt','hans@broughdesign.com',NULL,Now(),NULL,'Correspondence of the American Revolution; Being Letters of Eminent Men to George Washington, from the Time of His Taking Command of the Army to the End of His Presidency, Volume II., Jared Sparks, 1853');
